A review of the college at Garverville, east Belfast, was ordered after 54 student officers were found to have cheated in their exams. It also found that the college had a history of bullying, intimidation and bullying and that it had failed to deal with allegations that it had encouraged the cheating by some students.

The report concluded that the college has been the subject of serious shortcomings that have led to the students who were caught to have received poor quality grades. It identified a pattern of problems, including:

– a lack of oversight which fosters a culture of cheating;

– a failure to deal with allegations of bullying and intimidation;

– a lack of supervision which emboldens students to cheat;

– the bullying of members of staff and the failure to address concerns about bullying and intimidation;

– a failure to develop appropriate and effective mechanisms to promote discipline;

– a lack of robust procedures in relation to the monitoring of student progress;
